data.text:
Grateful for the time we spent onsite this week with the scheduling team at ENT of Georgia South. 

We had the chance to sit alongside Precious, Kimberly, and Tina (who keeps everything running!) as they onboarded to using Assort‚Äôs voice AI to answer patient calls. 

We listened in on real patient calls, asked questions, and got a firsthand look at how things work on the ground.

These in-person moments allow our team to think beyond technology. They remind us that building helpful tools means truly understanding the people using them: their workflows, their challenges, and what a good day looks like for their team.

Thank you to the ENT of GS crew for the warm welcome and for letting us learn with you üôè

Wait, is AI accurate when automating administrative healthcare tasks or not? The answer is ‚Äòexceptionally accurate‚Äô (nearly 100%, aka ‚Äòbetter than humans‚Äô, when done right), but I‚Äôm on 3 separate threads discussing this topic due to a ‚Äòsurprising‚Äô finding from medHELM benchmarking on LLM accuracy.¬† 

The finding generating the debate was that across 121 real-world medical tasks, models had the lowest performance for administrative and workflow tasks (eg, billing, appointment logic)‚Ä¶exactly the areas where teams want to apply AI for efficiency and cost savings!  But concern about AI accuracy for healthcare administrative tasks would be a misinterpretation of the finding. 

Studying how the highest impact companies using AI to automate healthcare administrative tasks have achieved high performance - I look at Brellium, Assort Health and Assured in this article - reveals 3 key points: a) information requirements, b) task orchestration and modularizing alongside polymorphic automation, and c) testing and refinement methods. 

Hope this sheds some light on how medical practices are deploying these solutions with confidence to grow revenue, reduce cost, accelerate time to revenue, ease team burdens, and improve care!

#AI #Healthcare #LLMs #Automation

data.text:
**Lesson 1 from 1 Million Patient Visits: The Power of Patient Stories**

We track outcomes, patient satisfaction, survey data, and proprietary benchmarks ‚Äì but nothing is more captivating than hearing an individual patient‚Äôs story.

Seeing the dramatic improvement that our physicians and APPs are making in real people‚Äôs lives is what keeps us going.

Patient testimonials are critical for two key stakeholders:
1Ô∏è‚É£ The first audience is pretty obvious ‚Äî prospective patients who are in pain but aren‚Äôt sure if what we do is right for them. When they see a patient‚Äôs story that resonates with their own pain journey, they know they are coming to the right place. Authentic video testimonials are a powerful marketing tool.
2Ô∏è‚É£ The second audience may be less obvious ‚Äî the supporting clinical and non-clinical team. These are the team members who have many touchpoints along the patient journey, but don‚Äôt always get to see the patients healed.

Think about it:
-The new patient scheduling team only hears patients at their worst ‚Äî without seeing the positive impact they had by booking that first appointment.
-The prior authorization team knows they fought to get a procedure approved ‚Äî but did they see the outcome?
-The ASC staff supported the procedure to fix the source of the pain ‚Äî but were they there for the follow-up visit when the patient shared their results?

Recently, Ramis Gheith, MD, FASA shared a few of his patient stories with our non-clinical team and there wasn‚Äôt a dry eye in the room. The impact we make as a team ‚Äî both directly and indirectly ‚Äî is the common thread that keeps us all going.

üéìLesson: Testimonials don‚Äôt just motivate patients ‚Äî they remind our team why the work matters.

#1millionpatients

data.text:
New feature drop: sibling scheduling for pediatrics.

When we analyzed voice transcripts from our pediatric clinics, a pattern jumped out: Parents were calling twice in a row. Once for Maya. Then again for Elias.

It wasn‚Äôt user error. It was a product gap. We learned that the call came from one parent booking appointments for two of their children. One after another.

The parent had called to book an appointment for one child‚Ä¶ then hung up, and called again to schedule for the second.

And that‚Äôs not a rare edge case; it happens quite often.

So we fixed it.

Here‚Äôs how our voice AI for pediatrics makes it work:

- Patient-first identity verification: HIPAA-compliant flows that flex to each clinic, like verifying DOB before revealing names (or vice versa).
- Smarter visit type detection: assumes shared visit reasons, but adapts when needed ‚Äî no redundant Q&A.
- Back-to-back scheduling, automatically: finds time slots that minimize in-office waits or space out visits based on family preference.
- Per-patient insurance logic: siblings don‚Äôt always share coverage, the system confirms and processes insurance for each child individually.

All in one call ‚Äî averaging just 3.1 minutes.

It‚Äôs a small detail, but a big unlock for parents who are short on time (and patience).

The early feedback?
¬†‚ÄúVery smooth and easy.‚Äù
¬†‚ÄúReally satisfied.‚Äù
¬†‚ÄúEasy and convenient.‚Äù

We're excited to give you an inside look into our annual meeting! This year, we had the honor of gathering our investors to celebrate our longstanding Bay Area roots. Being based in Silicon Valley means we sit at the epicenter of the venture capital, technology, philanthropic, and sports ecosystems, and our deep history and relationships with each are core to what we do. We heard from Next Legacy's partners, Russ Hall, Ryan Nece, Ben Choi, Kelli Cullinane, John N. Ailanjian, CFA, and Jessie Jia Guo, who shared more about the venture environment and our strategy, highlighted key investment metrics, and explored what's next for the firm.

The day was filled with fascinating discussions from our guest speakers, including GP of Theory Ventures Tomasz Tunguz, LaunchDarkly's CEO Dan Rogers, Office of Reid Hoffman‚Äôs Content Strategist Ben Relles, and San Francisco 49ers GM John Lynch. They shared their expertise on a range of topics, from how investors think about AI, to the path to becoming a successful CEO, the way AI is shaping the way we interact with content, and what it takes to excel in a high-stakes sports environment. In the coming weeks, we look forward to highlighting the key insights that our knowledgeable speakers shared.

Thank you to the Next Legacy Partners team for your hard work in making this year's Annual Meeting an outstanding success! Ryan Nece Ben Choi Kelli Cullinane John N. üí• What an extraordinary day! We/Next Legacy Partners just hosted our annual Bridge Summit in San Fran! I can still feel the energy, the passion, and the sheer magic of connection that radiated from this incredible event. This isn't just a summit; it's a celebration of diversity, a testament to the power of coming together to create positive energy from authentic conversations. 

üåâ The Bridge Summit is where excellence collides, inspiration ignites, and friendships are forged. Imagine a room filled with pro athletes, philanthropists, artists, influencers, CEOs, VCs, and thought leaders from every field imaginable. Now, picture them not just mingling but truly connecting, learning from each other, and being inspired to create change. That's the magic of the Bridge Summit!

And let me tell you, this year's event didn't just meet expectations‚Äîit soared beyond them! The diversity in that room was a sight to behold. In a place like Silicon Valley, the mosaic of the people at the Bridge Summit stood out like a beautiful, vibrant tapestry of humanity. Because here's the truth: the magic of this event is the people!

Wow! The speakers we had this year were hands down the best ever! Why? Because they dared to be real, to be vulnerable, to share not just their successes but their struggles, too. To the over 250 attendees in that room, they were given a gift, dropping wisdom and inspiration all over. 

I am so proud of the incredible team at Next Legacy and all their effort to make this a special day. We work very hard to huddle up with the most talented people in venture capital. This is why we believe it is critical to give back and designed the summit to be an example of the way we support our ecosystem and serve as a resource to our diverse community. This is a culmination of our daily effort to be a bridge for our LP community to gain access to the top managers and companies in tech.

But you know what they say‚Äîsuccess is 1% inspiration and 99% perspiration. And the perspiration? This event would not have been possible without Margaret Luna‚Äîyou are a ROCK STAR! Your dedication, passion, and attention to detail made this the best Bridge Summit to date.

So, to everyone who was part of the Bridge Summit - whether you were an attendee, a speaker, or part of the organizing team - I want you to know that you're not just participating in an event. You're part of an important bridge that believes in the power of diversity, in the strength of authentic connections, and in the transformative potential of shared knowledge.

I'm soooo grateful for Carla Zakhem-Hassan and JPMorganChase for their wonderful support and partnership!!

It‚Äôs National Mental Health Awareness Month. 


I want to remind everyone that taking care of your mental health should be a part of your everyday health and wellness routine.

It's easy to prioritize physical health over mental health, but the truth is that they are equally important. 

Your mental state affects every aspect of your life, from your relationships to your work performance, and it's crucial to consistently take care of it.

Don't let the stigma surrounding mental health prevent you from taking care of yourself.

Let's use this month as a reminder to prioritize our mental health and to support each other in doing so. 

Together, we can break the silence and promote a culture of mental wellness.

Wellness Of Joy Joy Vanichkul
